1 Executive Summary

Based on the findings in Meat Industry Strategic Plan, the red meat industry’s key output is consumer products. The expectations of consumers and communities – in Australia and overseas – in relation to quality, integrity and production are on the rise. One key issue for the industry is the inability to increase the tenderness of the product. If this issue can be resolved, it will create more consistency for consumers and lead to product differentiation.

Actindin is an enzyme which is naturally found in the kiwifruit. It is known for improving tenderness in red meat, which can be used in the production of better products. The data set shows the statistical results of the impact of actinidin, derived from kiwifruit, on consumer sensory outcomes for tenderness. Meanwhile, we are also interested in other factors that may potentially affect consumer sensory outcomes such as the muscle the sample is from, aging period for the sample and cooking methods.

The main discoveries are:

  • There is enough evidence to suggest that kiwifruit extract treatment does have independent effect on improving tenderness for meat.
  • There are interactions between differing cooking methods and the application of kiwi extract in affecting meat tenderness.However, the interaction effect on tenderness of meat between aging period and cut/muscle, as well as aging period and cooking method is not significant.
  • Different cooking methods affect tenderness score independently.
  • The differences of the aging periods of 10 days and 28 days do not have significant influence on mean tenderness score of meat.
  • There is a statistically significant differences of the tenderness between the different cuts of the muscles.

2.4 Research Questions

To examine an overall inquiry into whether the kiwifruit extract treatment has a statistically significant improvement on tenderness, we must first consider if the extract has a significant effect independently. Then, we account for other possible variables that were also introduced in the cooking process, including factors like aging periods, cuts/muscles as well as differing cooking methods.

Then, we could look at whether there are differences in between cooking methods, aging periods and muscles that affect tenderness respectively.

Finally, it is also important to evaluate the size of these statistical differences by considering if tenderness plays an active role in informing the overall satisfaction of consumers, thus confirming whether the kiwifruit extract has a notable and meaningful positive difference detectable by consumers.

2.4.1 Does the kiwifruit extract treatment improve tenderness?

In considering the effects of kiwifruit extract treatment on tenderness, we must first examine the data and consider whether it satisfies underlying assumptions of ANOVA, including independence, normality and equal variance for each of its groups.

Firstly, we can confirm that the sample is independent and identically distributed as the knowing about sample X (meat with kiwi extract treatment) cannot give you information about sample Y (meat without kiwi treatment), thus satisfying independence. Both subsets also follows a consistent distribution as seen in the visualisation below.

We first utilise a box plot and qqplots to visualise the data.

2.4.1.1 Part A: 2 sample t-test

Firstly, we run a 2 sample t-test to test as a preliminary for whether the application of kiwi extract treatment has a statistically significant enhancement on the tenderness of meat.

Hypothesis:

Let \(μ_X\) and \(μ_Y\) be the population mean for tenderness of meat treated with the kiwi extract (Enhanced) and those not treated with the kiwi extract (Control) respectively.

\(H_0: μ_X = μ_Y\)

\(H_1: μ_X \geqslant μ_Y\)

Assumptions:

\(X_1,…,X_n\) and \(Y_1,…,Y_n\) (the data) is independent and identically distributed.

The groups (Enhanced \(X_i\) and Control \(Y_i\)) are independent from one another.

Both groups have equal variance and is normally distributed: \(N(μ_X, σ^2)\) and \(N(μ_Y, σ^2)\).

The assumptions have been considered and satisfied above, as the assumptions for a 2-sample t-test is identical to ANOVA.

Test statistic:

\(T=\frac{\bar{X} −\bar{Y}}{S_p \sqrt{\frac{1}{n1} +\frac{1}{n2}}}\) where \(S_p^2 = \frac{(n_x-1)S_x^2 + (n_y-1)S_x^2}{n_x+n_y-2}\). Under \(H_0, T~t n_x+n_y-2\)

#Performing statistical test
##Manual 2 sample t-test

enhanced = filter(df, kiwi == "Enhanced")$tender
control = filter(df, kiwi == "Control")$tender

nS = length(enhanced)
nN = length(control)
sS = sd(enhanced)
sN = sd(control)
sP = sqrt(((nS - 1) * sS^2 + (nN - 1) * sN^2)/
            (nS + nN - 2))

xbarS = mean(enhanced)
xbarN = mean(control)
deg_free = nS+nN-2

t0 = (xbarS - xbarN) / ( sP * sqrt(1/nS+1/nN) ) 
p_val = (1-pt(abs(t0),deg_free))
c(round(t0,5), round(p_val, 5))
## [1] 4.02700 0.00003

Observed test statistic:

Thus, the observed test statistic is 4.027, and the degrees of freedom is \(468+581-2 = 1047\)

P-value

We can confirm the result with the R in-built 2 sample t-test.

## 2 sample t-test (assuming variance equal)
t.test(enhanced, control, alternative = 'greater', var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  enhanced and control
## t = 4.027, df = 1047, p-value = 3.029e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  2.792594      Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  57.08514  52.36139

Conclusion:

As the p-value, p ≈ 0.00003 < 0.05 (with level of significance at 5%) is consistent with manual calculations, there is sufficient evidence to reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level of significance. Thus we conclude that there is strong evidence to suggest that there’s a statistically significant enhancement/increase in tenderness for meat with applied the kiwi extract compared to meat which did not.

Visualising the data accords with our conclusion as well as there does appear to be discernible differences between the Enhanced and Control Groups in regards to tenderness.

living = ggplot(df,aes(x = tender, fill = kiwi))+

However, this does not account for the influence of many other treatment factors and their interaction with the kiwi extract (as well as blocks) in influencing tenderness. This can potentially invalidate our conclusion if we do not account for them. In building a sufficient ANOVA model that accommodates for all relevant interactions, factors and blocks, we must include them all and then omit those that are irrelevant so that degrees of freedom/residuals are not taken up unnecessarily and hence reduce the power of our hypothesis tests.

2.4.1.2 Part B: two-factor ANOVA test for interaction

To that effect, we now consider whether there is an interaction between kiwi extract and other treatment factors (including Dry Age, Cut, Cook) through a series of two-factor ANOVA test for interaction.

An appropriate model formula for a two-way ANOVA is as follows:

\(Y_{ijk}=μ+α_i+γ_j+(αγ)_{ij}+ε_{ijk}\)

Where μ is the overall mean, \(α_i\) and \(γ_j\) are treatment effects (differences between treatment group means and the overall mean),\((αγ)_{ij}\) are the interaction effects and \(ε_{ijk}∼N(0,σ2)\). We also require the following constraints:

\(∑_iα_i=0\) \(∑_jγ_j=0\) For each j, \(∑_i(αγ)_{ij}=0\) For each i, \(∑_i(αγ)_{ij}=0\)

Thus for our example, we are going to analyse the interaction effects of kiwi extract and differing cooking methods. This will form a generalized procedure for our remaining interaction test, as the procedures applied are almost identical (with the exception that the i and j, the number of categories within each variable could potentially change).

Let \(a_i\) be the treatment effects of kiwi extract (with 2 categories: Enhanced & Control) and \(γ_j\) be the treatment effects of the cooking method (with 4 categories: GRL, RST, RST-C20, RST-C10)

Hypothesis:

\(H_0: (αγ)_{ij}=0\) for all \(i=1,2\) and \(j=1,2,3,4\) \(H_1:\) not all \((αγ)_{ij}=0\)

Assumptions:

ANOVA assumes the residuals follow a normal distribution with constant variance. We have checked this above using a scatter plot of the residuals against the fitted values for homoskedasticity in constant error variance over the range of fitted values and a normal quantile plot as discussed above.

Test statistic:

#optional (tabulates data)
df %>% group_by(kiwi, cook) %>% summarise(
  xbar = mean(tender),
  n = n())
## # A tibble: 8 x 4
## # Groups:   kiwi [2]

          palette = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "lightblue3", "gray"))

a1 = aov(tender ~ kiwi * cook, data = df)
summary(a1)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## kiwi           1   5784    5784  16.516 5.19e-05 ***
## cook           3   4975    1658   4.735  0.00275 ** 
## kiwi:cook      3   3889    1296   3.701  0.01146 *  
## Residuals   1041 364562     350                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The Test statistic = Mean Sq Interaction/Mean Sq Residual = 1296/350 = \(3.701\)

It also follows an F distribution with \((a-1)(b-1) = (4−1)(2−1) = 3\) and \(ab(n-1) = 1041\) degrees of freedom under \(H_0\).

Observed test statistic:

As we can see from the graph, the observed test statistic, \(t_0 = 3.701\)

P-value:

\(P(F_{3,1041}≥ t_0)=P(F_{3,1041}≥3.701)= 0.011\)

Conclusion:

As the p-value, p ≈ 0.011 < 0.05 (with level of significance at 5%), there is sufficient evidence against \(H_0\) at the 5% level of significance to suggest that the interaction effects are not zero. Thus we should retain the interaction term in the model.

library(emmeans)

By generating an interaction plot, we can see numerous intersections that suggest there are interactions between differing cooking methods and the application of kiwi extract in affecting meat tenderness. This also accords with our conclusion above.

2.4.1.3 PART C: 2-way ANOVA with additional factors & blocks

Having found that the interaction term is not significant, we can proceed to consider whether or not there are any differences between the means of the main effects. Namely, we can now affirm our initial conclusion of Kiwi Extract significantly enhancing tenderness (as a result of our 2 sample t-test) with an corresponding ANOVA test that accounts for the presence and interaction of relevant factors within our sampled data. This new model will also account for blocks.

The relevant formula for this 2-way ANOVA test includes:

\(Y_{ijk}=μ+α_i+γ_j+b_k+c_l+(αγ)_{ij}+(αb)_{ik}+ (αc)_{il}+(bc)_{kl}+d_m+e_n+ε_{ijk}\)

Where μ is the overall mean, \(α_i, γ_j, b_k, c_l\) the treatment effects (differences between treatment group means and the overall mean) of kiwi, aging, cook and cut respectively, with \((αγ)_{ij}, (αb)_{ik}, (αc)_{il}, (bc)_{kl}\) as the relevant interaction effects (non-significant ones excluded). Additionally, \(d_m, e_n\) are the blocking variables -carcass weight and the unique identifier for a cow respectively. Finally, the residual is represented as \(ε_{ijk}∼N(0,σ2)\). We also require the following constraints:

\(∑_iα_i=0\) \(∑_jγ_j=0\) \(∑_kb_k=0\) \(∑_lc_l=0\) \(∑_md_l=0\) \(∑_ne_l=0\)

For each j, \(∑_i(αγ)_{ij}=0\) For each i, \(∑_i(αγ)_{ij}=0\) For each i, \(∑_i(αb)_{ik}=0\) For each k, \(∑_i(αb)_{ik}=0\)

(…and so on for each remaining interaction effect)

Let α1 and α2 be the treatment effects for the two levels of the Kiwi Extract variable (Enhanced and Control, respectively).

Hypothesis:

\(H0: α1=α2=0\)

\(H1:\) not all \(α_i\) equal to 0

Assumptions:

ANOVA assumes the residuals follow a normal distribution with constant variance. We have checked this above using a scatter plot of the residuals against the fitted values for homoskedasticity (constant error variance over the range of fitted values) and a normal quantile plot for normality as discussed above.

final= aov(tender ~ kiwi*cook + kiwi*d_aged + kiwi*cut + cook*cut + carcase_no + key_1, data = df)
summary(final)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## kiwi          1   5784    5784  50.319 2.56e-12 ***
## cook          3   4975    1658  14.427 3.40e-09 ***
## d_aged        1   3568    3568  31.041 3.30e-08 ***
## cut           2 221053  110526 961.560  < 2e-16 ***
## carcase_no    1    324     324   2.821  0.09338 .  
## key_1        85  23416     275   2.397 2.70e-10 ***
## kiwi:cook     3   1093     364   3.168  0.02373 *  
## kiwi:d_aged   1    922     922   8.020  0.00473 ** 
## kiwi:cut      1    758     758   6.591  0.01040 *  
## cook:cut      6   8810    1468  12.775 6.62e-14 ***
## Residuals   944 108508     115                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Test statistic

The Test statistic = Mean Sq Interaction/Mean Sq Residual

It also follows a F distribution with \(a−1\) and \(ab(n−1)\) degrees of freedom under \(H_0\).

Observed test statistic:

As we can see from the ANOVA summary table (or roughly similar manually \(5784/115 = 50.296\)), the observed test statistic is \(t_0 = 50.319\).

P-value:

\(P(F_{1,944}≥ t_0)=P(F_{1,944}≥50.319) < 0.00001\)

Conclusion:

As the p-value, p < 0.00001 is significantly less than 0.05 (with level of significance at 5%), there is overwhelming evidence against \(H_0\) at the 5% level of significance to suggest a statistically significant enhancement/increase in tenderness for meat which applied the kiwi extract compared to meat which did not.

2.4.2 Other general Questions

Following the primal question, we are interested to test whether there’s significant differences in tenderness of meat with the existence of other factors.

Do other factors, namely cooking methods, aging periods and muscles/cut affect tenderness?

2.4.2.1 Are tenderness different between cooking methods?

df %>% ggplot(aes(x = cook , y = (tender), fill = tender)) +
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip() +
  theme_classic(base_size = 32)

df %>% ggplot(aes(sample = tender, colour = cook)) +
  geom_qq() + geom_qq_line() +
  facet_wrap(~cook) +
  theme_classic(base_size = 18)

As per above, we through the visualisation of the qq-plots mostly fits well and in align with the lines, hence the normality assumption of the ANOVA test is likely satisfied. Moreover, the 4 groups of cooking methods has approximately similar variances as indicated by the boxplots with similar mean and distributions. Only RCT-C2 (roast, cold, 2mm slice) has a comparably smaller variance. Hence, as all assumptions are likely satisfied we continue with the tests.

This 2-way ANOVA test includes the consideration of the significant interaction effects and effective blocks:

\(Y_{ijk}=μ+α_i+(αγ)_{ij}+(αb)_{ik}+d_m+e_n+ε_{ijk}\)

Where μ is the overall mean, \(α_i\) the treatment effects of aging period, with \((αγ)_{ij}, (αb)_{ik}\) as the relevant interaction effects (non-significant ones excluded). Additionally, \(d_m, e_n\) are the blocking variables -carcass weight and the unique identifier for a cow respectively. Finally, the residual is represented as \(ε_{ijk}∼N(0,σ2)\). We also require the following constraints:

\(∑_iα_i=0\) \(∑_md_l=0\) \(∑_ne_l=0\) For each j, \(∑_i(αγ)_{ij}=0\) For each i, \(∑_i(αγ)_{ij}=0\) For each i, \(∑_i(αb)_{ik}=0\) For each k, \(∑_i(αb)_{ik}=0\)

Let α_1, α_2, α_3, α_4 be the treatment effects for the 4 different cooking methods of the meat, which takes values GRL (grill), RST (roast), RST-C10 (roast, cold, 10mm slice), RST-C2 (roast, cold, 2mm slice).

Hypothesis:

\(H0: α_1=α_2=α_3=α_4=0\)

\(H1:\) not all \(α_i\) equal to 0

Assumptions:

ANOVA assumes the residuals follow a normal distribution with constant variance. We have checked this above using a qqplot and box plot as discussed above.

Test statistic

The Test statistic = Mean Sq Interaction/Mean Sq Residual

It also follows a F distribution with \(a−1\) and \(ab(n−1)\) degrees of freedom under \(H_0\).

summary(aov(tender ~ cook + kiwi:cook +  cook:cut + carcase_no + key_1, data = df))

As the p-value, p < 0.00001 is significantly less than 0.05 (with level of significance at 5%), there is evidence against \(H_0\) at the 5% level of significance to suggest a statistically significant differences between the tenderness affected by the 4 different cooking methods of the meat.

2.4.2.2 Relationships between tenderness and aging periods?

Visualisation of the distribution of the tenderness in respect to the different aging periods.

df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = d_aged, y = tender),
                     fill = (tender)) +
  geom_boxplot() + coord_flip() +
  theme_classic(base_size = 32)

Both the sample groups seems have similar distribution and with a close to equal variance and normal distribution.

df %>% group_by(d_aged) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(tender), median = median(tender),
            min = min(tender), max = max(tender),
            var = var(tender), sd = sd(tender), n = n()) %>%knitr::kable(format = "markdown", digits = 3)
d_aged mean median min max var sd n
10 52.583 53.1 10.2 90.9 375.068 19.367 575
28 56.757 57.5 12.0 90.5 336.984 18.357 474

There seems to exist a difference in the means, where the 28 days aging period has a greater mean of 56.757 than the 10 days aging periods (52.583). We then test whether this is significant. We perform a 2 sample t-test to examine the significant of the differences between the means of the tenderness with different aging periods of 10 and 28 days.

Hypothesis \(H_{0}:\) \(\mu_{28days} = \mu_{10days}\) means for meat’s tenderness score aging 10 days and 28 days period have no difference

\(H_{1}:\)\(\mu_{28days} > \mu_{10days}\), the mean for 28 days aging is greater than the mean of 10 days aging period.

Assumptions Assuming that the samples \(X_1...,X_m\)are iid\(N(\mu x,\sigma^2)\),\(Y_1...,Y_m\) are iid \(N(\mu x,\sigma^2)\) and \(X_i's\) are independent of Y’s.

Checking assumptions:

As the aging period of 10 days does not affect the aging period of 28 days the 2 samples are independent of each other. Furthermore, the samples are iid. since the large samples size closing to normal distribution. Thus both the assumptions are satisfied, we continue the test.

t.test(tender ~ d_aged , data = df,alternative =  "greater", var.equal = TRUE )
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  tender by d_aged
## t = -3.5568, df = 1047, p-value = 0.9998
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -6.106371       Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 10 mean in group 28 
##         52.58267         56.75692

Test statistic

\(T =\) \(\dfrac{\bar X - \bar Y }{S_p \sqrt{1/n_1 +1/n_2} }\) Under \(H_0, T\)~ \(t_1047\)

Observed test statistic

\(t_0 = -3.5568\)

P-value:

\(P(t_0 \geq -3.5568) = 0.9998\)

Decision

The p-value for the two sample t-test is 0.9998 >0.05. Hence, we fail to reject the null hypothesis at the 5% level of significance and conclude that the there is no statistically significant difference between the mean of the tenderness with the differences of the aging periods of 10 days and 28 days.

2.4.2.4 Does tenderness affect overall liking of the meat?

Lastly, to confirm our assumptions, we check if tenderness does have an effect on the overall liking of participants to the meat.

# organising data
q5dat = data
tender = q5dat$Tender
ovl = q5dat$`O/all Like`

Visualising our data:

q5dat %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=tender, y=ovl)) +
  geom_point() + 
  labs(x = "Tenderness", y = "Overall Liking", title = "Customers' Overall Liking of Meat based on its Tenderness")

From the scatter plot generated, it looks like there is likely to be a relationship between tenderness and overall liking of the meat.

Since we are testing for correlation between two continuous variables (tenderness and overall liking), a Pearson’s correlation test is used (Puth et al., 2014).

Hypothesis:

\(H_0: ρ = 0\)

\(H_1: ρ ≠ 0\)

Assumptions:

Linearity and homoskedascity: the data for tenderness and overall liking are linearly related, as evident from the scatter plot above. Similarly, the data distribution is fairly homoskedastic and the plot takes on a tubular shape (rather than conical).

Outliers: the data is visualised below as box-plots, there are no apparent outliers visible.

Normality: from the box-plots constructed below, the data distribution looks approximately normal.

ggplot(q5dat, aes(x = "", y = tender)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_jitter(width=0.15, size = 1, colour = "red") + 
  theme_bw(base_size = 18) + 
  labs(x = "", y = "Meat tenderness")

ggplot(q5dat, aes(x = "", y = ovl)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_jitter(width=0.15, size = 1, colour = "red") + 
  theme_bw(base_size = 18) + 
  labs(x = "", y = "Overall Liking")

Test statistic:

cor.test(tender, ovl, method = "pearson", use = "complete.obs")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  tender and ovl
## t = 100.35, df = 1047, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9456991 0.9571375
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9517478

P-value:

Since the p value is less than 0.05, We can conclude that tenderness does have an effect on overall liking. Based on the scatter plot constructed, we can be be confident that this is a positive relationship.

Conclusion:

Since the p value is less than 0.05, We can conclude that tenderness does have an effect on overall liking. Based on the scatter plot constructed, we can be be confident that this is a positive relationship.


3 Conclusions

In summary, we arrive at the following conclusions:

  1. Kiwifruit extract does enhance the tenderness of the meat. p val < 0.00001

This finding comes as no surprise, since previous research has eluded to kiwi fruit extract’s ability to tenderise meat (Toohey et al., 2011)

  1. Cooking methods (p < 0.00001), ageing (p = 0.0004), and muscle groups (p < 0.00001) all affect tenderness.

This finding also comes as no surprise, since cooking methods and ageing are all processes designed to alter the texture of meat. It is also expected that different muscle groups have different levels of tenderness due to their different functions in terms of movement of the cow and therefore their different fat compositions and distributions.

  1. Tenderness has an effect on the customer’s overall liking of the meat.

This confirms the usefulness of kiwifruit extract as a meat tenderiser in improving the customer experience with meat. Furthermore, it is useful to confirm that cooking methods, ageing and choosing different muscle groups will have an effect on the customer’s overall liking and satisfaction of the meat by altering the tenderness of the meat.

3.1 Meaningfulness of these findings

All p-values found were smaller than or equal to 0.0004, values much smaller than our 0.05 cut-off. This indicates that our findings are meaningful, and that changes in use of kiwifruit extract, cooking methods, ageing and muscle groups will exert a major effect on the tenderness of the meat. Similarly, changes in tenderness will likely affect the customers’ overall liking of the meat.

3.2 Flaws and Future Research

Consumers were untrained and their rating of the meat may not be objective, therefore their ratings are also unstandardised and may vary even for the same meat and experience of the meat. It may be useful in the future to compare ratings of the same meat from untrained consumers and experts.

Grilled meat was heated to approximately 200C but variations in temperature may have affected the cooking of the meat. In the future, the cooking temperature of the meat should be more tightly controlled if possible.

The age of cattle at the time of slaughter was neither recorded nor standardised, although it is known that it affects the tenderness of meat (Xion et al., 2007). Therefore, future experiments should either control for age or record it as an additional factor.

Since actinidin has also been found to improve the tenderness of lamb (Han et al., 2009) and pork (Christensen et al., 2009), further exploration using similar parameter and protocols could prove useful and reveal ways to add value to cheaper cuts of meat from different animals. Additionally, similar experiments may investigate the effects of actinidin on the tenderness of traditionally tougher meats, such as mutton.

3.3 Closing Comments

Analysis of experimental results reveal promising uses of the kiwifruit protease actinidin in adding value to cheaper cuts of beef by improving its tenderness. Other methods to alter tenderness include ageing the meat, changing the method of its cooking, and choosing a more tender cut of meat.

These findings have potential to improve the eating experience of consumers, especially those that consume cheaper cuts of meat and are therefore more likely to be from a low socioeconomic background. Since food is such an integral part of daily living and beef is so commonly consumed, actinidin use in beef may improve the quality of life for many with lower incomes.
